threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis:
The provided PowerShell code initiates by opening a web browser to the specified URL "https://www.google.com/chrome/". Subsequently, it executes a series of commands using cmd to extract files from encrypted archives located in specific directories. These extracted files are then saved to the directory "C:\Users\Public\Documents\Documents". Finally, the code runs an executable file named "file.exe" from the aforementioned directory.

This script exhibits behavior commonly associated with malware, such as downloading additional payloads from the internet, extracting and executing files from encrypted archives, and running executables without clear context or justification. The actions performed by this code could potentially lead to unauthorized data exfiltration, system compromise, or other malicious activities.

The code begins by assigning the URL for Google Chrome to a variable named $url.
Next, it uses the Start-Process cmdlet to open the specified URL in the default web browser.
Following this, it executes a series of commands using the cmd /c command:
- The first command extracts the contents of the file VFS\ProgramFilesX64\25\25.exe to the location C:\Users\Public\Documents\Documents, using the password "Documents3".
- The second command extracts the contents of the file C:\Users\Public\Documents\Documents\Documents2.7z to the location C:\Users\Public\Documents\Documents, using the password "Documents2".
- The third command extracts the contents of the file C:\Users\Public\Documents\Documents\Documents1.7z to the location C:\Users\Public\Documents\Documents, using the password "Documents1".
Finally, it uses the Start-Process cmdlet again to execute the file C:\Users\Public\Documents\Documents\file.exe.
